Scitus signifying, as we have seen above, ‘knowing,’ ‘clever,' ‘smart,' is occasionally employed to denote personal attractions, and may be rendered ‘nice-looking5’ thus in Merc. IV. iv. 15, Satis scitum filum mulieris means, ‘not a bad-looking slip of a girl ;' and so again in v. 17. The diminutive scitulus bears the same meaning; thus Rud. 11.vii. 7, L. Qua sunt facie? S. Scitula. ‘L. What sort of looking girls are they? S. Pretty.' And again, Rud. IV. i. 3, iam cluentas reperi Atque ambas forma scitula atque aetatula.
